=== Subspecies ===
There are three accepted subspecies of the chestnut-vented nuthatch.<ref name="IOC">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/nuthatch/ |title=Nuthatches, Wallcreeper, treecreepers, mockingbirds, starlings & oxpeckers |date=22 October 2016 |publisher=[[International Ornithological Congress]] |version=6.4 |at=Family Sittidae |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222041438/http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/nuthatch/ |archive-date=22 December 2016 |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> 

* ''S. n. montium'' <small>([[John David Digues La Touche|La Touche]], 1899)</small>, described by the Irish ornithologist [[John David Digues La Touche|John La Touche]] (with the [[protonym]] ''Sitta montium'') as a montane taxon altitudinally separated from ''S. europaea sinensis'',<ref>{{cite journal |last=La Touche |first=John David Digues |date=1899 |url=https://archive.org/details/ibis57brit/page/404/mode/2up?view=theater |title=Note on the birds of North-west Fohkien |journal=[[Ibis (journal)|The Ibis]] |series=Series 7 |volume=5|issue=19 |pages=(403–)404 |via=Internet Archive|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1899.tb01490.x}}</ref> it occurs in eastern [[Tibet]], southern and eastern China, [[Myanmar]], and northwest [[Thailand]].<ref name="IOC"/>
* ''S. n. nagaensis'' <small>([[Henry Haversham Godwin-Austen|Godwin-Austen]], 1874)</small>, occurs in the Naga Hills in northeastern India and northwestern Myanmar.<ref name="IOC"/>
* ''S. n. grisiventris'' <small>([[Norman Boyd Kinnear|Kinnear]], 1920)</small>, described from [[Nat Ma Taung|Mount Victoria]] in western Myanmar, under the [[protonym]] ''Sitta europaea grisiventris'' (since ''S. n. nagaesis'' was also then considered a subspecies of the Eurasian nuthatch ''S. europaea'');<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kinnear |first=Norman Boyd |author-link=Norman Boyd Kinnear |date=31 May 1920 |url=https://archive.org/details/bulletinofb3840191720brit/page/142/mode/2up?view=theater |title=Mr. N. B. Kinnear exhibited and described a new form of Nuthatch from Burma|journal=[[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]] |volume=40 |page=142 |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> birds from southern [[Vietnam]] are also currently ascribed to this subspecies.<ref name="IOC"/>

The subspecies ''S. n. montium'' was considered to possibly be the result of [[Hybrid (biology)|hybridisation]] between chestnut-vented nuthatch and the Chinese subspecies of Eurasian nuthatch ''[[Eurasian nuthatch|Sitta europaea sinensis]]'',<ref name="McCarthy">{{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Eugene M.|url=http://www.spinus.info/Images/books/AH743697479746.pdf|title=Handbook of Avian Hybrids of the World|date=January 2006|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-518323-8|pages=246–247|chapter=Nuthatches - Family Sittidae}}</ref> or at least to be able to interbreed with it.<ref name="Harrap114–116">{{cite book |last=Harrap |first=Simon |others=Illustrated by David Quinn |title=Tits, Nuthatches and Treecreepers |date=1996|editor=[[Christopher Helm]] |publisher=[[Helm Identification Guides|Helm]]|isbn=0-7136-3964-4|pages=114–117}}</ref> This is possibly due to the fact that the [[type series]] of ''S. e. sinensis'' was composite and included a specimen of the chestnut-vented nuthatch. For these reasons, Jean-François Voisin and colleagues designated a [[lectotype]] in 2002 for the name ''Sitta sinensis'' <small>([[Jules Verreaux|Verreaux]], 1871)</small>.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Voisin|first1=C.|last2=Voisin|first2=J.-F.|last3=Causey|first3=Douglas|last4=Dickinson|first4=E. C.|name-list-style=amp|date=2002|title=Systematic notes on Asian birds. 29. On the types of ''Sitta sinensis'' J. Verreaux, 1871, and ''Sitta montium'' La Touche, 1899|url=https://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/display2.php/attachment.pdf?url=http%3A%2F%2Frepository.naturalis.nl%2Fdocument%2F46727|journal=[[Zoologische Verhandelingen]]|location=[[Leiden]]|volume=340|issue=27|pages=191–196|isbn=90-73239-84-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Dickinson|first=E. C.|date=2006|title=Systematic notes on Asian birds. 62. A preliminary review of the Sittidae|url=https://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/display2.php/attachment.pdf?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.repository.naturalis.nl%2Fdocument%2F41857|journal=[[Zoologische Verhandelingen]]|location=Leiden|volume=80|issue=14|pages=225–240}}</ref> The attribution of the populations of western Myanmar and southern Indochina to the same subspecies ''S. n. grisiventris'', with ''S. n. montium'' in central Myanmar between these populations seems untenable, and their taxonomy has yet to be verified.<ref name="HarrapBoW">{{cite journal|last=Harrap|first=Simon|name-list-style=amp|date=4 March 2020|title=Chestnut-vented Nuthatch (''Sitta nagaensis'')|url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/chvnut1/cur/introduction|version=1.0|publisher=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]]|doi=10.2173/bow.chvnut1.01|editor-last4=Christie|editor-first5=E.|editor-last5=de Juana|editor-first4=D. A.|editor-last2=Elliott|editor-first3=J.|editor-last3=Sargatal|editor-first2=A.|editor-first1=J.|editor-last1=del Hoyo|journal=Birds of the World|s2cid=216229068|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

== Description ==
=== Plumage and measurements ===
[[File: Chestnut-vented Nuthatch (Sitta nagaensis).jpg|alt=A white and grey bird eating a seed while perching on the branch of tree|right|thumb|''S. n. montium'' on Wawu Mountain, [[Hongya County]], Sichuan, China]]
The chestnut-vented nuthatch is a medium-sized nuthatch, measuring {{convert|12.5–14|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/><ref name="HarrapBoW"/> The {{birdgloss|upperparts}} are a solid blue-grey from [[crown (anatomy)|crown]] to tail, with a marked black [[Lore (anatomy)|loral]] line extending to the base of the wing. The {{birdgloss|underparts}} are pale grey, more or less tinted buff-tinged depending on the subspecies or the wear of the [[plumage]]; the dark brick-red back flanks contrast strongly with the rest of the underparts.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> The {{birdgloss|undertail coverts}}, which may be of the same colour depending on the subspecies, have a large white border at the end of the feathers or a white patch near the tip.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

The species does not show marked [[sexual dimorphism]]. The male's rear flanks are deep brick-red, deeper and less orange than the undertail coverts, whereas the female's flanks are rufous, concolorous with the undertail coverts. Females also have duller underparts, and juveniles are more buff than adults with worn plumage.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> The [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]] is brown to dark brown, the [[beak|bill]] is greyish-black to blackish with the base of the lower [[Beak#Mandibles|mandible]] (and sometimes the base of the upper) slate-grey or blue-grey. The legs are dark brown, greenish or blue-grey, with almost black claws.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

Three subspecies are accepted, but variation is essentially [[Cline (biology)|clinal]], with Chinese populations (''S. n. montium'') having buff underparts, which get duller and purer grey as they move southward in the species' distribution. In [[Northeast India]] and western Myanmar, ''S. n. nagaensis'' in fresh plumage is as buff as ''S. n. montium'' in worn plumage. In southern Vietnam and southwestern Myanmar, ''S. n. grisiventris'' has purer grey underparts than ''S. n. nagaensis''.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> Adults undergo a complete [[moult]] after the breeding season, from May to June, and an incomplete moult occurs before it.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

=== Similar species ===
[[File:White-tailed Nuthatch West Sikkim India 16.02.2016.jpg|alt=A white and orange-bellied bird perching|right|thumb|The [[white-tailed nuthatch]] (''S. himalayensis'') has uniform underparts and is much more colourful than the chestnut-vented nuthatch.]]
The range of the chestnut-vented nuthatch overlaps with that of the [[Burmese nuthatch]] (''S. neglecta''). However, the chestnut-vented nuthatch is easily distinguished by the colour of its underparts, and the lack of contrast between the sides of the head and the throat, whereas the other species has white chins, cheeks, and [[wikt:parotic#Adjective|parotid]] region contrasting with brick-red to orange-brown underparts. However, in the chestnut-vented nuthatch, some individuals in fresh plumage (especially in ''S. n. montium'') may have underparts almost as buff as some Burmese nuthatch females or juveniles. The chestnut-vented nuthatch can then be recognised by its darker, duller blue upperparts, by its red flanks contrasting with the buff, and by its undertail, with feathers edged with red giving a "scales" pattern, when they appear almost uniformly white in the Burmese nuthatch.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

The subspecies ''S. n. montium'' can also be confused with the subspecies ''S. e. sinensis'' of the Eurasian nuthatch (''S. europaea'') where they coexist in [[Sichuan]] and [[Fujian]]. As the latter subspecies has more orange underparts, some Eurasian females may be difficult to differentiate from chestnut-vented nuthatches in fresh plumage. The two species can be distinguished by their vocalisations, with chestnut-vented nuthatch lacking the characteristic singing ''dwip'' of the Euraisan nuthatch.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> Hybrids between these two taxa have been suggested,<ref name="McCarthy"/> with montane populations of ''S. e. sinensis'' being, like the chestnut-vented nuthatch, greyer on the underside, darker above, and larger than lowland individuals. The chestnut-vented nuthatch, however, is even greyer, and does not have the whitish cheeks of the Eurasian nuthatch.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

In southwest China, the chestnut-vented nuthatch lives within the range of the [[Yunnan nuthatch]] (''S. yunnanensis''). However, the latter is smaller, has a thin white [[supercilium]], and has plain, pale buff underparts with no russet on the flanks.<ref>{{cite book |last=Harrap |first=Simon |others=Illustrated by David Quinn |title=Chickadees, Tits, Nuthatches and Treecreepers |date=1995 |editor=[[Christopher Helm]] |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |page=143 |isbn=0-691-01083-8}}</ref> In northeastern India and northwestern Myanmar, the chestnut-vented nuthatch can also be confused with the white-tailed nuthatch (''S. himalayensis''); both species share similar habitats. The white-tailed nuthatch, however, has a white spot on the top of the middle [[rectrices]], and has more orange underparts, without brick-red flanks or white spots on the undertail.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> The [[giant nuthatch]] (''S. magna''), whose distribution overlaps with that of the chestnut-vented nuthatch in India, Myanmar, and Thailand, differs from the latter in being much larger in size, having a finer {{birdgloss|eyestripe}}, and having a {{birdgloss|crown}} that is much lighter than the rest of the {{birdgloss|mantle}}.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

== Ecology and behaviour ==
[[File:Yellow-cheeked Tit - Bhutan.jpg|alt=A black and yellow bird perching on the branch of tree|thumb|In winter, the [[yellow-cheeked tit]] (''Machlolophus spilonotus'') may roam with the nuthatch in mixed-foraging flocks.]]
The chestnut-vented nuthatch generally lives alone or in pairs, but joins [[mixed-species foraging flocks]] outside of the breeding season. In winter, it can thus be observed in the company of different species of [[Tit (bird)|tits]] (Paridae) such as the [[yellow-cheeked tit]] (''Maclolophus spilonotus''), [[Aegithalidae|bushtits]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stanford|first1=J. K.|author1-link=J. K. Stanford|last2=Ticehurst|first2=Claud B.|author2-link=Claud B. Ticehurst|name-list-style=amp|date=January 1938|title=On the Birds of Northern Burma. Part I|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1474-919X.1938.tb00185.x|journal=[[The Ibis]]|volume=80|issue=1|pages=65–102|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1938.tb00185.x|via=[[Wiley Online Library]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[woodpeckers]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schäfer |first1=Ernst |author1-link=Ernst Schäfer |last2=De Schauensee |first2=Rodolphe Meyer |author2-link=Rodolphe Meyer de Schauensee |date=1938 |title=Zoological Results of the Second Expedition to Dolan Western China and Eastern Tibet, 1934–1936. Part II: Birds |journal=[[Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia]] |volume=90 |pages=185–260 |jstor=4064251 }}</ref> [[Alcippe (bird)|alcippes]], and [[Red-tailed minla|minlas]].<ref name="Matthysen"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stanford|first1=J. K.|last2=Mayr|first2=Ernst|author2-link=Ernst Mayr|year=2008|title=The Vernay-Cutting Expedition to Northern Burma. Part II|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1474-919X.1941.tb00596.x|journal=[[The Ibis]]|volume=83|issue=1|pages=56–105|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1941.tb00596.x|via=Wiley Online Library|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

=== Vocalisations ===
{{Birdsong|image=SittaNagaensis.png|species=''Sitta nagaensis''|url=https://xeno-canto.org/explore?query=Sitta%20nagaensis}}
The chestnut-vented nuthatch's calls are varied, with squeaky ''sit'' or ''sit-sit'' sounds, repeated more or less rapidly with various inflections and in irregular series. Similar but drier ''{{Not a typo|tchip}}'' or ''{{Not a typo|tchit}}'' sounds are sometimes made, often in a [[Trill (music)|trill]] reminiscent of the alarm of a [[Eurasian wren]] (''Troglodytes troglodytes''). The alarm calls of the chestnut-vented nuthatch are reported in English-language literature as nasal sounds in ''{{Not a typo|quir}}'', ''{{Not a typo|kner}}'' or ''{{Not a typo|mew}}'', as well as an emphatic, metallic ''{{Not a typo|tsit}}'', sometimes doubled or repeated in quick series. The song is a stereotyped, monotonous [[Ratchet (instrument)|rattle]] or [[tremolo]] in ''{{notatypo|chichichichichi}}&nbsp;...'' or ''{{notatypo|trr-rrrrrrr-ri}}&nbsp;...'', lasting less than a second or sometimes slowed down to ''{{notatypo|chi-chi-chi-chi-chi}}&nbsp;...'' or ''{{notatypo|diu-diu-diu- diu-diu}}'' reminiscent of the song of the Eurasian nuthatch.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

=== Food ===
The chestnut-vented nuthatch often forages for food on the ground, on rocks, old stumps, or in trees.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> No specific information about the diet is known, but the species probably feeds on small [[arthropods]] and [[seeds]].<ref name="HarrapBoW"/>

=== Breeding ===
Although the breeding season varies by region, it generally takes place in Thailand from March to May, March to June for [[India]], April to early June for eastern Myanmar, and April to May in Fujian. On [[Nat Ma Taung]], juveniles have been observed as early as March 31. According to observations made in Thailand and Vietnam, the construction of the nest begins in January. It is located at a height of about {{convert|10|m|in|abbr=on}} in the hole of a tree, or in a stump.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

The chestnut-vented nuthatch, like the Eurasian nuthatch and other species of the family, may line the entrance of a cavity with mud to reduce the opening and thus avoid [[predation]] of the brood. The bottom of the nest is lined with pieces of bark and [[moss]] and topped with hair. Two to five eggs are laid, averaging {{convert|18.6|×|13.8|mm|in|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} in ''S. n. nagaensis'' and {{convert|18.3|×|14|mm|in|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} in ''S. n. montium''. They are white, with red dots on a mottled reddish-purple background, the red dots mainly concentrated at the larger end of the egg.<ref name="HarrapBoW" /><ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

==Distribution and habitat==
The chestnut-vented nuthatch lives from Tibet to the mountains of [[Lâm Đồng province]] in southern [[Vietnam]].<ref name="Harrap114–116"/><ref name="IOC"/> In India, it is found only in the far eastern states of [[Arunachal Pradesh]], [[Nagaland]], [[Manipur]], [[Assam]] and [[Meghalaya]]. The species lives in the [[Chin Hills]] of western [[Myanmar]], but most of its distribution in Myanmar is in the eastern half of the country, from [[Kachin State]] to at least [[Shan State]], and also into northwestern [[Thailand]]. It also nests in Tibet and south-central China, from western Sichuan to [[Yunnan]] and marginally in southwestern [[Guizhou]]. An isolated Chinese population also lives in northwestern Fujian, on [[Mount Huanggang]].<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> Two other isolated populations from the southernmost part of the species' distribution, one occurring in southern Vietnam on the [[Đà Lạt Plateau]],<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> another being reported in Laos on the [[Bolaven Plateau]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Robson |first=Craig |date=September 2005 |title=New Holland Field Guide to the Birds of South-East Asia |publisher=[[New Holland Publishers]] |page=210 |isbn=978-1-84330-746-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Duckworth |first1=J. W. |last2=Tizard |first2=R. J. |last3=Timmins |first3=R. J. |last4=Thewlis |first4=R. M. |last5=Robichaud |first5=W. G. |last6=Evans |first6=T. D. |name-list-style=amp |date=1998 |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5c1a9e03f407b482a158da87/t/5c1fbe3888251bb6cac14f37/1545584194551/Duckworth-Laos.pdf |title=Bird records from Laos, October 1994-August 1995 |journal=[[Forktail (journal)|Forktail]] |volume=13 |pages=33–68}}</ref> 

The chestnut-vented nuthatch usually inhabits [[evergreen forests]] of the uplands, or forests and pine patches growing on dry ridges in the middle of evergreen forests. Locally, it also occurs in [[Temperate deciduous forest|deciduous forests]] in northeastern India, in ''[[Quercus subsericea]]'' oak forests and [[alder|alder groves]] in northeastern Myanmar, [[Picea|spruce]] forests (''Picea'' sp.), [[Abies|fir]] forests (''Abies'' sp.) or [[rhododendron]] stands in Yunnan, or [[Populus|poplar]] (''Populus'' sp.) and [[Juglans|walnut]] (''Juglans'' sp.) in Sichuan.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> The altitudinal distribution ranges from {{convert|1400–2600|m|ft|abbr=on}} in India, Thailand, and Myanmar, occasionally occurring up to {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} in the latter. It also occurs from {{convert|1050–3500|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Tibet and Sichuan and up to {{convert|4570|m|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} in Yunnan. The population in southern Vietnam lives between {{convert|915–2285|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/>

== Status and threats ==
The population of the chestnut-vented nuthatch is declining due to [[habitat destruction]] and fragmentation, but its range is large and was estimated to be 3.8&nbsp;million&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (1.5&nbsp;million square miles),<ref name="iucn status 17 November 2021"/> and the species is generally common throughout its range.<ref name="Harrap114–116"/> For these reasons, the chestnut-vented nuthatch is considered to be of [[least concern]] by the [[International Union for the Conservation of Nature]].<ref name="iucn status 17 November 2021"/> A study carried out in 2009 tried to predict the impact of [[climate change]] on the distribution of several species of nuthatches in Asia by modeling two scenarios. It predicted that the chestnut-vented nuthatch could see its distribution decrease between the 2040s and 2069 by 15.9 to 17.4%.<ref name="Menon">{{cite journal |last1=Menon |first1=Shaily |last2=Islam |first2=M. Zafar-ul |last3=Peterson |first3=A. Townsend |name-list-style=amp |date=31 August 2003 |url=http://scholarworks.gvsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1005&context=biopeerpubs |title=Projected climate change effects on nuthatch distribution and diversity across Asia |journal=[[The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology]] |volume=57 |issue=2 |pages=569–575}}</ref>

